<chapter xml:id="chapter-power-series" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
<title>Power and Taylor series</title>

<section xml:id="section-power-series-motivation">
<title>Motivation</title>

<p>
In <xref ref="section-seq-motivation" />,
we looked at approximating <m>\ln(1.001)</m> with Taylor polynomials of increasing degree.
We now have the framework to recognize these approximate values as a <em>sequence of partial sums</em> for the infinite series
<md> \sum_{k = 1}^\infty \frac{{(-1)}^{k - 1} {0.001}^k}{k} </md>.
Using Taylor polynomials of higher degree should yield better approximations.
This corresponds to taking partial sums including more terms to better approximate the sum value of the infinite series.
Will the full infinite series recover the <em>exact</em> value of <m>\ln(1.001)</m>?
</p>

<p>
Before we explore that question,
also consider that we may use Taylor polynomials based at a specific point to approximate output values of the function at <em>all</em> input values sufficiently near that point.
In other words,
the infinite series in the example of approximating <m>\ln(1.001)</m> above is only one example in an infinite family of such approximation examples.
Using the pattern of Taylor polynomials based at <m>t = 1</m> arrived at in <xref ref="example-poly-approx-logarithm-at-1" />,
for <em>any</em> input value <m>t</m> with <m>t \approx 1</m>,
we could say
<md> \ln(t) \approx \nthtaylor{1}(t) = \sum_{k = 1}^n \frac{{(-1)}^{k - 1} {(t - 1)}^k}{k} </md>.
There are several variables involved in the expressions above.
There is index variable <m>k</m> for the summation notation.
There is also the degree <m>n</m> of the Taylor polynomial used,
but as above we are going to let that trend to <m>\infty</m> as we consider partial sums of an infinite series.
And finally there is the input variable <m>t</m> that makes a Taylor polynomial a function.
In this chapter we will study infinite series that involve such an <q>input variable</q>.
</p>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-power-series-definition">
<title>Power series</title>

<subsection>
<title>Basics</title>

<definition xml:id="definition-power-series">
	<title>Power series</title>
	<statement><p>
		An infinite series involving non-negative powers of an indeterminate <m>t</m>: <md> \sum_{k = 0}^\infty a_k t^k </md>,
		using the convention <m>t^0 = 1</m> for all values of <m>t</m> (including <m>t = 0</m>).
		The sequence <m>\nseq{a}</m> is called the <term>coefficient sequence</term> for the power series.
	</p></statement>
</definition>

<example><p>
	The power series <m>\sum t^k / k!</m> has partial sum functions <md> s_n(t) = \sum_{k = 0}^n \frac{t^k}{k!} </md>.
	If you completed <xref ref="exercise-poly-approx-maclaurin-exp" />,
	then you should recognize these partial sums as precisely the Maclaurin polynomials for <m>\exp(t)</m>.
</p></example>

<p> If we attempt to use a power series as a function we may run into trouble. </p>

<example xml:id="example-power-series-first-look-at-domain"><p>
	Define <md> f(t) = \sum_{k = 1}^\infty \frac{t^k}{k} </md>.
	For <m>t = -1</m>,
	we have <md> f(-1) = \sum_{k = 1}^\infty \frac{{(-1)}^k}{k} </md>,
	which is the alternating harmonic series.
	We saw in <xref ref="example-series-alt-harmonic-cond-conv" /> that this series converges conditionally,
	and in <xref ref="example-series-reordering-terms-different-results" /> we investigated its sum value numerically,
	determining that <m>f(-1) = \ln(2)</m>.
	On the other hand,
	for <m>t = 1</m> we have <md> f(1) = \sum_{k = 1}^\infty \frac{1}{k} </md>,
	the regular harmonic series,
	which we know diverges.
</p></example>

<p>
<xref ref="example-power-series-first-look-at-domain" /> demonstrates that,
viewed as a function in the indeterminate variable,
the domain of a power series is tied to convergence/divergence of the infinite series that results from substituting particular values for that variable.
We will say that a power series <m>\sum a_k t^k</m> <term>converges at <m>t = c</m></term> if the infinite series <m>\sum a_k c^k</m> converges.
For a domain set <m>D</m> of input values,
we will say that the power set <term>converges on <m>D</m></term> if it converges for all <m>c</m> in <m>D</m>.
And similarly with <q>converges</q> replaced by <q>diverges.</q>
</p>

<example><p>
	The power series <m>\sum t^k</m> is a geometric series for each value of <m>t</m>,
	and we know the base values for which a geometric series converges.
	So we can say that this power series converges on domain <m>-1 \lt t \lt 1</m> and diverges on domains <m>t \le -1</m> and <m>t \ge 1</m>.
</p></example>

<p>
We know that convergence of an infinite series depends on the terms being added trending to <m>0</m> sufficiently quickly.
So if a power series converges at a particular <m>t</m>-value,
it should also converge at all smaller <m>t</m>-values.
</p>

<fact xml:id="fact-power-series-radius">

	<statement><p><ol>

		<li xml:id="fact-power-series-radius-converge">
			If <m>\sum a_k t^k</m> converges at <m>t = c</m>,
			then it also converges <em>absolutely</em> on domain <m>-\abs{c} \lt t \lt \abs{c}</m>.
		</li>

		<li xml:id="fact-power-series-radius-diverge">
			If <m>\sum a_k t^k</m> diverges at <m>t = c</m>,
			then it also diverges on both <m>t \lt -\abs{c}</m> and <m>t \gt \abs{c}</m>.
		</li>

	</ol></p></statement>

	<proof><title>Justification for <xref ref="fact-power-series-radius-converge" text="type-local">Statement</xref></title><p>
		If <m>\sum a_k t^k</m> converges at <m>t = c</m>,
		this means that the infinite series <m>\sum a_k c^k</m> converges.
		We must then have <m>\seq{a_n c^n} \to 0</m>,
		and so there is some tail <m>\seqtail{a_n c^n}</m> completely contained in the range <m>(-1, 1)</m>.
		For every value of <m>t</m> in the domain <m>-\abs{c} \lt t \lt \abs{c}</m>,
		we have <m>\abs{t / c} \lt 1</m>,
		and so the geometric series <m>\sum {\abs{t / c}}^k</m> converges (absolutely).
		But with <m>\abs{a_n c^n} \lt 1</m> for <m>n \ge N</m>,
		we have
		<md>
			<mrow> \abs{a_n t^n} \amp = \abs{a_n t^n} \cdot \abs{\frac{c^n}{c^n}} </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp = \abs{a_n c^n} \cdot \abs{\frac{t^n}{c^n}} </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp \lt {\abs{\frac{t}{c}}}^n </mrow>
		</md>
		for all <m>n \ge N</m>.
		So <m>\sum \abs{a_k t^k}</m> converges by comparison with the geometric series <m>\sum {\abs{t / c}}^k</m>.
	</p></proof>


	<proof><title>Justification for <xref ref="fact-power-series-radius-diverge" text="type-local">Statement</xref></title><p>
		This is effectively the contrapositive of <xref ref="fact-power-series-radius-converge" text="type-local">Statement</xref>.
		If <m>\sum a_k c^k</m> diverges,
		then it is not possible for <m>\sum a_k t^k</m> to converge for any <m>t \gt \abs{c}</m>,
		because if it did then <xref ref="fact-power-series-radius-converge" text="type-local">Statement</xref> says that <m>\sum a_k t^k</m> would also converge for all values of <m>t</m> of smaller magnitude,
		which includes <m>c</m>.
		But <m>\sum a_k c^k</m> diverges.
		And similarly for <m>t \lt - \abs{c}</m>.
	</p></proof>

</fact>

</subsection>

<subsection>
<title>Radius of convergence</title>

<p>
For a specific power series <m>\sum a_k t^k</m>,
<xref ref="fact-power-series-radius" /> gives us a pretty clear picture of the pattern of convergence at different <m>t</m>-values:
<ul>
	<li>
		If the series converges at a particular non-zero <m>t</m>-value,
		then it also converges at every <m>t</m>-value of smaller magnitude,
		positive and negative.
		This creates a symmetric <term>interval of convergence</term> on the real number line,
		centred at <m>0</m>.
	</li>
	<li>
		If the series diverges at a particular non-zero <m>t</m>-value,
		then it also diverges at every <m>t</m>-value of larger magnitude,
		positive and negative.
		This creates a symmetric <q>void</q> region on the real number line,
		centred at <m>0</m>,
		outside of which the series diverges.
	</li>
</ul>
It follows that there must be a boundary between the two patterns above:
a boundary between <m>t</m>-values with small enough magnitude for the series to converge,
and <m>t</m>-values magnitude too large for convergence.
A symmetric pair of points <m>t = \pm R</m> on either size of <m>0</m>,
with convergence at all points in between and divergence at all points outside.
</p>

<identity xml:id="pattern-power-series-radius">

	<statement>
		<p>
		For a power series <m>\sum a_k t^k</m> there exists a non-negative (possibly infinite) value <m>R</m>,
		called the <term>radius of convergence</term>,
		for which the series converges for all <m>t</m>-values satisfying <m>-R \lt t \lt R</m> and diverges for all <m>t</m>-values satisfying <m>t \lt -R</m> or <m>t \gt R</m>.
		</p>
	</statement>

	<proof><p>
		Consider the set <m>\convset{C}</m> of non-negative <m>t</m>-values for which the series converges.
		Note that <m>\convset{C}</m> is non-empty,
		since every power series of the form <m>\sum a_k t^k</m> converges to <m>a_0</m> at <m>t = 0</m>.
		If set <m>\convset{C}</m> is unbounded,
		then <xref ref="fact-power-series-radius" /> implies that the series must converge at <em>all</em> <m>t</m>-values,
		so take <m>R = \infty</m>.
		Otherwise,
		if set <m>\convset{C}</m> is bounded then it must have a least upper bound.
		Take <m>R</m> to be that least upper bound value.
	</p></proof>

</identity>

<remark><p>
	<xref ref="pattern-power-series-radius" /> does not say anything about convergence/divergence at <m>t = \pm R</m> for a reason.
	In the examples below, we will see that different power series can exhibit different behaviours at the boundaries of its interval of convergence:
	some series converge at both <m>t = \pm R</m>,
	some diverge at both points,
	and some converge at one and diverge at the other.
</p></remark>

<p>
In the examples below,
we will most often use the <xref ref="pattern-series-ratio-test" text="title" />,
as two consecutive powers of <m>t</m> will cancel to a single <m>t</m> in a ratio:
<md> \frac{a_{k + 1} t^{k + 1}}{a_k t^k} = \frac{a_{k + 1}}{a_k} \; t </md>.
However,
sometimes the <xref ref="pattern-series-root-test" text="title" /> is useful,
depending on the form of the coefficient sequence <m>\nseq{a}</m>.
</p>

<p>
Also,
we will generally test for <em>absolute</em> convergence,
which implies convergence
(<xref ref="fact-series-absolute-conv" />).
Because we know that convergence is dependent on the magnitude of the <m>t</m>-values and not the sign
(except possibly right at <m>t = \pm R</m>),
and that the interval of convergence is symmetric on the number line about <m>t = 0</m>,
introducing an absolute value will help measure the maximum magnitude of <m>t</m> for convergence.
</p>

<example>
	<title>A power series that only converges <em>within</em> its radius of convergence</title>
	<p>
	We know that the Geometric Series <m>\sum t^k</m> converges only for <m>-1 \lt t \lt 1</m>,
	and not at either <m>t = \pm 1</m>,
	or at any <m>t</m>-value of larger magnitude.
	</p>
</example>

<example xml:id="example-power-series-opposite-endpoints">
	<title>Two series that converge only at one endpoint of the interval of convergence</title>
	<p><ol>

		<li xml:id="example-power-series-opposite-endpoints-left-converge-right-diverge">

			<p>
			Let's apply the <xref ref="pattern-series-ratio-test" text="title" /> to test the power series <md> \sum_{k = 1}^\infty \frac{t^k}{k} </md> for absolute convergence.
			We have
			<md> \abs{\frac{t^{n + 1} / (n + 1)}{t^n / n}} = \frac{n}{n + 1} \cdot \abs{t} \to 1 \cdot \abs{t} \quad \text{as } n \to \infty </md>.
			Recall that the Ratio Test says that the series converges if this limit is less than <m>1</m>,
			diverges if it is greater than <m>1</m>,
			and the test provides no information if the limit is exactly <m>1</m>.
			So we have (absolute) convergence when <m>\abs{t} \lt 1</m>,
			which corresponds to the interval <m>-1 \lt t \lt 1</m>,
			and have divergence when <m>\abs{t} \gt 1</m>,
			which corresponds to the regions <m>t \lt -1</m> and <m>t \gt 1</m>.
			Our radius of convergence is <m>R = 1</m>.
			</p>

			<p>
			But what about at the endpoints <m>t = \pm 1</m>?
			At <m>t = 1</m> we get the harmonic series,
			which we know diverges,
			but at <m>t = -1</m> we get the alternating harmonic series,
			which we know (conditionally) converges.
			So the complete interval of convergence is <m>-1 \le t \lt 1</m>.
			</p>

		</li>

		<li xml:id="example-power-series-opposite-endpoints-left-diverge-right-converge">

			<p>
			Analyzing absolute convergence of the power series <md> \sum_{k = 1}^\infty \frac{{(-1)}^k t^k}{k} </md>
			leads to the same calculation and the results as above,
			since the absolute value brackets will nullify the alternating <m>{(-1)}^k</m> factor in the terms.
			So again we have <m>R = 1</m>,
			with (absolute) convergence when on domain <m>-1 \lt t \lt 1</m> and divergence on domains <m>t \lt -1</m> and <m>t \gt 1</m>.
			But this time the behaviour at the endpoints has flipped,
			since substituting <m>t = -1</m> will again nullify the alternating sign pattern in the coefficient sequence and leave us with the divergent harmonic series,
			whereas substituting <m>t = 1</m> will maintain the alternating pattern and leave us with the convergent alternating harmonic series.
			So the complete interval of convergence is <m>-1 \lt t \le 1</m>.
			</p>

		</li>

	</ol></p>

</example>

<example>
	<title>A series that converges at both endpoints</title>
	<p>
	Again we use the <xref ref="pattern-series-ratio-test" text="title" /> to test the power series <md> \sum_{k = 1}^\infty \frac{t^k}{k^2} </md> for absolute convergence:
	<md> \abs{\frac{t^{n + 1} / (n + 1)^2}{t^n / n^2}} = {\left(\frac{n}{n + 1}\right)}^2 \; \abs{t} \to 1^2 \cdot \abs{t} \quad \text{as } n \to \infty  </md>.
	So the radius of convergence is <m>R = 1</m>.
	At one endpoint of the interval of convergence,
	when <m>t = 1</m> we have the convergent <m>p</m>-series <m>\sum 1 / k^2</m>.
	At the other endpoint,
	when <m>t = -1</m> we have the alternating <m>p</m>-series <m>\sum {(-1)}^k / k^2</m>.
	But this series converges absolutely,
	so it converges as well,
	and our complete interval of convergence is <m>-1 \le t \le 1</m>.
	</p>
</example>

<example>
	<title>A series with <m>R = 0</m></title>
	<p>
	For <m>\sum (k!) t^k</m> we have
	<md> \abs{\frac{(n + 1)! \cdot t^{n + 1}}{n! \cdot t^n}} = (n + 1) \; \abs{t} \to \infty \quad \text{as } n \to \infty </md>.
	In particular, for every non-zero value of <m>t</m>,
	no matter how small,
	the factorial will eventually overwhelm the powers of <m>t</m> and so <m>a_k t^k \not\to 0</m>,
	which means that the sum cannot converge.
	So <m>R = 0</m> and the sum <em>only</em> converges (to <m>0! = 1</m>) for <m>t = 0</m>.
	</p>
</example>

<example>
	<title>A series with <m>R = \infty</m></title>
	<p>
	For <md> \sum_{k = 0}^\infty \frac{{(-1)}^k x^k}{2^k \cdot k!} </md>
	we have
	<md>
		\abs{\frac{{(-1)}^{n+1} t^{n+1} / 2^{n + 1} (n+1)!}{{(-1)}^n t^n / 2^n n!}}
		= \frac{\abs{t}}{2 (n + 1)}
		\to 0 \quad \text{as } n \to \infty
	</md>.
	Thus this series converges for all values of <m>t</m>.
	</p>
</example>

<p>
From our examples so far you might think that <m>0</m>, <m>1</m>, and <m>\infty</m> are the only possibilities for a radius of convergence.
Here is an example with radius of convergence <m>R = 2</m>.
But if you replace the occurrences of the number <m>2</m> in this example by any other positive number,
you can generate an example with that radius of convergence,
demonstrating that any positive number is possible as a radius of convergence of some power series.
</p>

<example>
	<title></title>

	<p>
	Consider <m>\sum t^k / 2^k</m>.
	This time we will use the <xref ref="pattern-series-root-test" text="title" /> to test absolute convergence:
	<md> \sqrt[n]{\abs{\frac{t^n}{2^n}}} = \frac{\abs{t}}{2} </md>.
	No limit is necessary,
	as this result is constant relative to the index variable <m>n</m>.
	But as with the Ratio Test we need this <q>limit</q> result to be less than <m>1</m> to have convergence,
	and <m>\abs{t} / 2 \lt 1</m> occurs when <m>\abs{t} \lt 2</m>,
	so our radius of convergence is <m>R = 2</m>.
	</p>

	<p>
	At endpoint <m>t = -2</m> the power series becomes
	<md> \sum_{k = 0}^\infty \frac{{(-1)}^k {(-2)}^k}{2^k} = \sum_{k = 0}^\infty \frac{1}{2^{k - 1}} </md>
	which is a convergent geometric series.
	At the other endpoint <m>t = 2</m> we have
	<md> \sum_{k = 0}^\infty \frac{{(-1)}^k 2^k}{2^k} = \sum_{k = 0}^\infty \frac{{(-1)}^k}{2^{k - 1}} </md>.
	But we have already established above that this series converges absolutely,
	hence it converges.
	</p>

</example>

<warning><p>
	When applying the Ratio or Root tests to a power series,
	make sure you are considering the limit as <m>n \to \infty</m>,
	<alert>not</alert> as <m>t \to \infty</m>.
</p></warning>

</subsection>

<subsection>
<title>Shifted power series</title>

<p>
With inspiration from Taylor series,
we may also wish to consider horizontal shifts of power series:
<md> \sum a_k {(t - c)}^k </md>.
Using a change of variables <m>u = t - c</m> we can express this as a <q>normal</q> power series,
<md> \sum a_k u^k </md>,
which we know will have a radius of convergence <m>R</m>,
so that the series converges for all values of <m>u</m> satisfying <m>-R \lt u \lt R</m>.
In terms of the original indeterminate <m>t</m>,
we (unsurprisingly) end up with a shifted interval of convergence as well:
<md alignment="gather">
	<mrow> -R \lt t - c \lt R </mrow>
	<mrow> c - R \lt t \lt c + R </mrow>
</md>.
So we still have a radius of convergence <m>R</m>,
but the interval of convergence is now centred at <m>t = c</m> instead of at <m>t = 0</m>.
As before,
the series will diverge outside of that interval,
and convergence/divergence at the endpoints needs to be separately investigated.
</p>

<example><p>
	The shifted power series <md> \sum_{k = 0}^\infty \frac{k {(t + 2)}^k}{3^{k + 1}} </md> will have an interval of convergence centred at <m>t = -2</m>.
	As usual, we use the <xref ref="pattern-series-ratio-test" text="title" /> to test the absolute convergence:
	<md>
		<mrow>
			\abs{ \frac{(n + 1) {(t + 2)}^{n + 1} / 3^{n + 2}}{n {(t + 2)}^n / 3^{n + 1}} }
			\amp = \abs{ \frac{(n + 1) (t + 2) / 3}{n} }
		</mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{n + 1}{3 n} \abs{t + 2} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp \to \frac{1}{3} \abs{t + 2} </mrow>
	</md>
	as <m>n \to \infty</m>.
	So the series converges for
	<md alignment="gather">
		<mrow> \frac{1}{3} \abs{t + 2} \lt 1 </mrow>
		<mrow> \abs{t + 2} \lt 3 </mrow>
		<mrow> -3 \lt t + 2 \lt 3 </mrow>
		<mrow> -5 \lt t \lt 1 </mrow>
	</md>.
	From the second inequality above,
	our radius of convergence is <m>R = 3</m>,
	and the interval of convergence has endpoints <m>t = -5</m> and <m>t = 1</m>.
	At those endpoints,
	we know from the third inequality above that <m>t + 2 = \pm 3</m>,
	and the series becomes
	<md> \sum_{k = 0}^\infty \frac{k {(\pm 3)}^k}{3^{k + 1}} = \sum_{k = 0}^\infty \frac{k {(\pm 1)}^k}{3} </md>.
	Whether the series is alternating (at <m>t = -5</m>) or not (at <m>t = 1</m>),
	it diverges because the magnitude of the terms diverge to infinity.
	Thus the interval of convergence is as initially stated above,
	where both endpoints are excluded.
</p></example>

</subsection>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-power-series-taylor">
<title>Taylor series</title>

<introduction><p>
	In this section our analysis will focus primarily on Maclaurin series,
	as Taylor series are just shifts of Maclaurin series.
	But since Maclaurin series are just special cases of Taylor series,
	we will refer to all as <term>Taylor series</term>.
</p></introduction>

<subsection xml:id="subsection-power-series-creating-taylor">
<title>Creating Taylor series</title>

<p>
Recall that the general pattern for a Taylor polynomial based at <m>t = 0</m>
(that is, a Maclaurin polynomial)
for a function <m>f</m> is
<md> \nthtaylor{0}(t) = \sum_{k = 0}^n \frac{\nthderiv[k]{f}(0)}{k!} \; t^k </md>,
where <m>\nthderiv{f}</m> represents the <m>\nth</m> derivative of <m>f</m>
(and <m>\nthderiv[0]{f}</m> is just <m>f</m> itself).
If <m>\nthderiv{f}(0)</m> exists for all <m>n</m>,
then we can consider <m>\nthtaylor{0}</m> as a partial sum of a power series,
where we just allow the coefficient pattern to continue indefinitely.
</p>

<definition>
	<title>Taylor series at <m>0</m></title>
	<statement><p>
		If all orders of derivative value for function <m>f</m> exist at <m>t =0</m>,
		then the power series
		<md> T_0(t) = \sum_{k = 0}^\infty \frac{\nthderiv[k]{f}(0)}{k!} \; t^k </md>
		is called the <term>Taylor series at <m>0</m> for <m>f</m></term>.
	</p></statement>
</definition>

<p>
Taylor series for different functions will have different radii of convergence,
depending on the pattern of derivative values at <m>t = 0</m>.
On its interval of convergence,
we can in some sense think of the sequence of Taylor polynomials <q>converging</q> to the Taylor series:
<md> \nthtaylor{0} \overset{?}{\to} T_0 \quad\text{as}\quad n \to \infty </md>.
</p>

<example xml:id="example-power-series-exp-taylor">
	<title>Taylor series for the natural exponential function</title>
	<p>
	We know that <m>\nthderiv{\exp}(t) = \exp(t)</m> for all <m>n</m>,
	so <m>\nthderiv{\exp}(0) = 1</m> for all <m>n</m>.
	Thus the Taylor series at <m>0</m> is
	<md> \sum_{k = 0}^\infty \frac{t^k}{k!} = 1 + t + \frac{t^2}{2} + \frac{t^3}{3!} + \frac{t^4}{4!} \dotsb </md>.
	Using the <xref ref="pattern-series-ratio-test" text="title" /> we have
	<md> \abs{ \frac{t^{n + 1} / (n + 1)!}{t^n / n!} } = \frac{\abs{t}}{n + 1} \to 0 \quad\text{as } n \to \infty </md>.
	Since this limit is always less than <m>1</m>,
	the Taylor series for the natural exponential function converges for <em>all</em> values of <m>t</m>.
	</p>
</example>

<example xml:id="example-power-series-shifted-logarithm">
	<title>Taylor series for shifted logarithm</title>
	<p>
	Consider <m>f(t) = \ln(1 + t)</m>.
	Since <m>d(1 + t)/dt = 1</m>,
	applying the Chain Rule to the derivatives of <m>f(t)</m> is simple.
	Let's look for the pattern in the derivatives.
	<md>
		<mrow>
			f(t) \amp = \ln(1 + t)
			\amp \nthderiv[4]{f}(t) \amp = - \frac{3 \cdot 2}{{(1 + t)}^4}
		</mrow>
		<mrow>
			f'(t) \amp = \frac{1}{1 + t}
			\amp \nthderiv[5]{f}(t) \amp = \frac{4 \cdot 3 \cdot 2}{{(1 + t)}^5}
		</mrow>
		<mrow>
			f''(t) \amp = - \frac{1}{{(1 + t)}^2}
			\amp \amp \vdots
		</mrow>
		<mrow>
			f'''(t) \amp = \frac{2}{{(1 + t)}^3}
			\amp \nthderiv{f}(t) \amp = {(-1)}^{n - 1} \, \frac{(n - 1) \cdot \dotsm \cdot 3 \cdot 2}{{(1 + t)}^n}
		</mrow>
		<mrow> \amp \amp \amp \vdots </mrow>
	</md>
	At <m>t = 0</m>,
	for <m>n \ge 1</m> this simplifies to <md> \nthderiv{f}(t) = {(-1)}^{n - 1} \; (n - 1)! </md>.
	So for <m>n \ge 1</m> the Taylor series coefficient pattern is
	<md> \frac{\nthderiv{f}(0)}{n!} = \frac{{(-1)}^{n - 1} \; (n - 1)!}{n!} = \frac{{(-1)}^{n - 1}}{n} </md>.
	The initial term <m>f(0)</m> does not fit into this pattern,
	but in fact <m>f(0) = \ln(1) = 0</m> so it doesn't have to.
	Thus the Taylor series is
	<md> T_0(t) = \sum_{k = 1}^\infty \frac{{(-1)}^{k - 1}}{k} \; t^k = t - \frac{t^2}{2} + \frac{t^3}{3} - \frac{t^4}{4} + \dotsb </md>,
	where we begin the sum at index <m>0</m> because <m>f(0) = 0</m>.
	The calculations in <xref ref="example-power-series-opposite-endpoints" /> demonstrate that this series converges absolutely.
	At <m>t = 1</m> this is an alternating harmonic series,
	which we know converges.
	At <m>t = -1</m> this is the negative of the harmonic series,
	and so diverges.
	(But <m>t = -1</m> is not in the domain of <m>\ln(1 + t)</m> anyway.)
	So the Taylor series for <m>\ln(1 + t)</m> at <m>t = 0</m> converges on interval <m>-1 \lt t \le 1</m>.
	</p>
</example>

<example>
	<title>Taylor series for cosine</title>
	<p>
	In <xref ref="example-poly-approx-maclaurin-cos" /> we determined the general pattern for a Maclaurin polynomial for cosine to be
	<md> \nthmaclaurin (t) = \sum_{m = 0}^{\floor{n/2}} \frac{{(-1)}^m}{(2m)!} \; t^{2 m} </md>.
	Recall that the polynomial only involves even powers of the indeterminate because every second higher derivative value evaluates to <m>0</m> at <m>t = 0</m>.
	To obtain the Taylor series at <m>t = 0</m> for cosine we use the same pattern:
	<md> T_0(t) = \sum_{m = 0}^{\infty} \frac{{(-1)}^m}{(2m)!} \; t^{2 m} = 1 - \frac{t^2}{2} + \frac{t^4}{4!} - \frac{t^6}{6!} + \dotsb </md>.
	Using the <xref ref="pattern-series-ratio-test" text="title" /> we have
	<md>
		\abs{\frac{{(-1)}^{m + 1} t^{2 (m + 1)} / \bbrac{2(m+1)}!}{{(-1)}^m t^{2 m} / (2 m)!}}
		= \frac{t^2}{(2m+2)(2m+1)}
		\to 0 \quad\text{as } m \to \infty
	</md>.
	So the Taylor series for cosine at <m>t = 0</m> converges for all values of <m>t</m>.
	</p>
</example>

<exercise xml:id="exercise-power-series-taylor-for-sine">
	<title>Taylor series for sine</title>
	<p>
	Use the Maclaurin polynomial pattern you developed in <xref ref="exercise-poly-approx-maclaurin-sin" /> to create the Taylor series at <m>t = 0</m> for the sine function,
	and investigate its convergence.
	</p>
</exercise>

<warning><p>
	When computing a Taylor series,
	<alert>do not</alert> substitute <m>t = 0</m> until you see the pattern of <em>all</em> higher derivatives of <m>f</m>.
</p></warning>

</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="subsection-power-series-taylor-limits">
<title>Limits of Taylor series</title>

<p>
We have looked at a number of examples of Taylor series <xref ref="subsection-power-series-creating-taylor" /> and investigated their convergence.
But to what do they converge?
When we created Taylor polynomials,
our goal was to approximate functions with simpler polynomial functions,
and we reasoned that higher-degree polynomials should be better approximations by capturing more of the behaviour of the original function.
Being an <q>infinite-degree</q> polynomial,
does the Taylor series for a function become an <q>infinitely-good</q> approximation of the original function?
</p>

<p>
To answer this question,
we should first remember what it means for a series to <term>converge</term> to a sum value:
the sequence of partial sums should approach that value.
Partial sums for a Taylor series are simply Taylor polynomials,
and to measure how close a Taylor polynomial value
(evaluated at some particular <m>t</m>-value in the interval of convergence for the Taylor series)
is to a potential limiting value,
we can consider the difference between the partial sum value and the potential limiting value.
(See <xref ref="fact-seq-conv-vs-conv-to-zero" />.)
And the <q>potential limiting value</q> we propose is the original function value at <m>t</m>.
</p>

<definition>
	<title>Remainder sequence for a Taylor series</title>
	<statement><p>
		Given a function <m>f</m> for which the derivative values <m>\nthderiv{f}(t^\ast)</m> exist for all <m>n</m>,
		for each <m>n</m> define <term>remainder function</term> <m>\nthremainder{t^\ast}(t) = f(t) - \nthtaylor{t^\ast}(t)</m>.
	</p></statement>
</definition>

<fact xml:id="fact-power-series-taylor-remainder">

	<statement><p>
		If <m>\bbseq{\nthremainder{t^\ast}(t)} \to 0</m> for a particular value of <m>t</m>,
		then the Taylor series <m>T_{t^\ast}(t)</m> for <m>f</m> converges at <m>t</m> to the value of <m>f(t)</m>.
	</p></statement>

	<proof><p>
		By definition,
		at a particular <m>t</m>-value the series <md> T_{t^\ast}(t) = \sum_{k = 0}^\infty \frac{\nthderiv[k]{f}(t^\ast)}{k!} \, {(t - t^\ast)}^k </md>
		converges if the sequence of partial sum values <m>\bbseq{\nthtaylor{t^\ast}(t)}</m> converges for that value of <m>t</m>.
		But since <m>\nthremainder{t^\ast}(t) = f(t) - \nthtaylor{a}(t)</m>,
		<xref ref="fact-seq-conv-vs-conv-to-zero" /> says that <m>\bbseq{\nthremainder{t^\ast}(t)} \to 0</m> is equivalent to <m>\bbseq{\nthtaylor{t^\ast}(t)} \to f(t)</m>.
	</p></proof>

</fact>

<remark><p>
	It is tempting to think of <m>\bbseq{\nthtaylor{t^\ast}(t)}</m> as a sequence of <em>functions</em>,
	converging to the <em>function</em> <m>f(t)</m>.
	But in <xref ref="fact-power-series-taylor-remainder" />,
	the reality is that <m>\bbseq{\nthtaylor{t^\ast}(t)}</m> is a sequence of <em>numbers</em> at a specific value of <m>t</m>,
	converging to a specific function output <em>value</em> <m>f(t)</m>.
	We have not
	<!-- TODO yet? Will uniform convergence be added to these notes? -->
	developed the conceptual tools necessary to discuss <term>sequences of functions</term> and their convergence.
	At this point,
	the correct thing to say about <m>\bbseq{\nthtaylor{t^\ast}(t)} \to f(t)</m> is that this convergence occurs <term>pointwise</term>.
	(That is, this convergence may be valid or invalid at different points on the <m>t</m> number line.)
</p></remark>

<p>
Recall that we have already stated a bound on the error in approximating <m>f(t) \approx \nthtaylor{t^\ast}(t)</m> for a specific value of <m>t</m>
(<xref ref="fact-poly-approx-taylor-error" />).
Since <m>\nthremainder{t^\ast}(t)</m> is measures that error,
we have
<md> \abs{\nthremainder{t^\ast}(c)} \le \frac{M}{(n + 1)!} \, {\abs{c - t^\ast}}^{n + 1} </md>,
where <m>M</m> is the maximum value of <m>\abs{\nthderiv[n+1]{f}(t)}</m> on the domain between <m>c</m> and <m>t^\ast</m>,
inclusive.
</p>

<example xml:id="example-power-series-natural-exp-taylor-remainder">
	<title>Remainder of a Taylor approximation to the natural exponential function</title>
	<p>
	In <xref ref="example-power-series-exp-taylor" /> we determined that Taylor series for the exponential function at <m>t = 0</m> converges for all values of <m>t</m>.
	For all <m>n</m> we have <m>\nthderiv{\exp}(t) = \exp(t)</m>,
	and since the exponential function is an increasing function,
	on any given domain <m>0 \le t \le c</m> we have <m>\abs{\nthderiv[n+1]{\exp}(t)} \le e^c</m>.
	Thus <md> \abs{\nthremainder{0}(c)} \le \frac{e^c}{(n + 1)!} \, {\abs{c - 0}}^{n + 1} </md>.
	In the ratio <md> \frac{{\abs{c}}^{n+1}}{(n + 1)!} </md>,
	each of the numerator and denominator is a product of <m>n + 1</m> factors.
	But the factors in the numerator are all the same magnitude,
	while those in the denominator become arbitrarily large,
	and we conclude that <md> \frac{{\abs{c}}^{n+1}}{(n + 1)!} \to 0 \quad \text{as } n \to \infty </md>.
	By the Squeeze Theorem,
	we must also have <m> \abs{\nthremainder{0}(c)} \to 0</m>.
	And a similar argument can be made to demonstrate the same for negative <m>c</m>.
	We conclude that the Taylor series for the exponential function converges to the value of the exponential function at all points;
	that is,
	<md> e^t = 1 + t + \frac{t^2}{2} + \frac{t^3}{3!} + \frac{t^4}{4!} + \dotsb </md>
	is always true.
	In particular,
	using <m>t = 1</m> gives us an alternative definition of Euler's number:
	<md> e = \sum_{k = 0}^\infty \frac{1}{k!} </md>.
	</p>
</example>

<exercise xml:id="exercise-power-series-cosine-taylor-remainder">
	<title>Evaluating Taylor series for sine and cosine</title>
	<p> Demonstrate that the Taylor series for sine and cosine at <m>t = 0</m> both converge to the value of their respective originating function for all values of <m>t</m>. </p>
</exercise>

</subsection>

</section>

<section>
<title>Functions defined by power series</title>

<introduction>

	<p>
	Any input-output process defines a function.
	And any power series <m>\sum a_k t^k</m> defines such a process:
	if the input value <m>t</m> is in the interval of convergence of the series,
	then the output value is the limiting value of the sequence of partial sums for that value of <m>t</m>.
	For example,
	we have already seen that the natural exponential function is equivalent to the power-series-defined function <m>f(t) = \sum t^k/k!</m>.
	</p>

	<p>
	If we are to view power series as functions,
	a number of questions arise.
	<ul>
		<li>
			How do we determine where power series functions are continuous, hence integrable?
			How do we integrate power series functions?
		</li>
		<li>
			How do we determine where power series functions are differentiable,
			and how do we compute their derivatives?
		</li>
	</ul>
	</p>

	<p>
	Throughout this chapter we will explore and state results for Taylor series based at <m>t = 0</m> and for power series of the form <m>\sum a_k t^k</m>,
	but all results are true for Taylor series at other base points and for <q>shifted</q> power series.
	</p>

</introduction>

<subsection>
<title>Term-by-term integration/differentiation</title>

<p>
Let's first consider a power series that is a Taylor series at <m>t = 0</m> for a function for which <m>\nthderiv{f}(0)</m> is defined for all <m>n</m>:
<md> f(0) + f'(0) \, t + \frac{f''(0)}{2} \, t^2 + \frac{f'''(0)}{3!} \, t^3 + \frac{\nthderiv[4]{f}(0)}{4!} \, t^4 + \dotsb </md>.
Suppose <m>F</m> is an antiderivative for <m>f</m>.
By definition, this means that <m>F'(t) = f(t)</m>.
But then
<md><mrow> F''(t) \amp = f'(t) \amp F'''(t) \amp = f''(t) \amp \amp \cdots \amp \nthderiv[k]{F}(t) \amp = \nthderiv[k - 1]{f}(t) \amp \amp \cdots </mrow></md>,
and so the Taylor series for <m>F</m> based at <m>t = 0</m> is
<md>
	<mrow> \amp F(0) + F'(0) \, t + \frac{F''(0)}{2} \, t^2 + \frac{F'''(0)}{3!} \, t^3 + \frac{\nthderiv[4]{F}(0)}{4!} \, t^4 + \dotsb </mrow>
	<mrow> = \;\; \amp F(0) + f(0) \, t + \frac{f'(0)}{2} \, t^2 + \frac{f''(0)}{3!} \, t^3 + \frac{f'''(0)}{4!} \, t^4 + \dotsb </mrow>
	<mrow> = \;\; \amp F(0) + f(0) \, t + f'(0) \cdot \frac{t^2}{2} + \frac{f''(0)}{2!} \cdot \frac{t^3}{3} + \frac{f'''(0)}{3!} \cdot \frac{t^4}{4} + \dotsb </mrow>
</md>.
Let's line this Taylor series up with the one for f.
<md>
	\begin{array}{cccccccccccc}
		f\colon \amp \amp \amp f(0) \amp + \amp f'(0) \, t \amp + \amp {\displaystyle \frac{f''(0)}{2} \, t^2} \amp + \amp {\displaystyle \frac{f'''(0)}{3!} \, t^3} \amp + \amp \dotsb
		\\
		F\colon \amp F(0) \amp + \amp f(0) \, t \amp + \amp {\displaystyle f'(0) \cdot \frac{t^2}{2}} \amp + \amp {\displaystyle \frac{f''(0)}{2!} \cdot \frac{t^3}{3}} \amp + \amp {\displaystyle \frac{f'''(0)}{3!} \cdot \frac{t^4}{4}} \amp + \amp \dotsb
	\end{array}
</md>
It appears that each term of the series for <m>F</m> can be obtained by <term>term-by-term integration</term> of the series for <m>f</m>
(see <xref ref="pattern-poly-int-power-positive-exp" text="type-local">Formula</xref> in <xref ref="pattern-poly-int-power" />),
along with the introduction of an arbitrary constant term <m>F(0)</m>.
</p>

<p>
Now consider the Taylor series based at <m>t = 0</m> for the derivative of <m>f</m>.
Let <m>g</m> represent the derivative of <m>f</m>,
so that
<md><mrow> g(t) \amp = f'(t) \amp g'(t) \amp = f''(t) \amp \amp \cdots \amp \nthderiv[k]{g}(t) \amp = \nthderiv[k + 1]{f}(t) \amp \amp \cdots </mrow></md>.
So the Taylor series for <m>g</m> based at <m>t = 0</m> is
<md>
	<mrow> \amp g(0) + g'(0) \, t + \frac{g''(0)}{2} \, t^2 + \frac{g'''(0)}{3!} \, t^3 + \frac{\nthderiv[4]{g}(0)}{4!} \, t^4 + \dotsb </mrow>
	<mrow> = \;\; \amp f'(0) + f''(0) \, t + \frac{f'''(0)}{2} \, t^2 + \frac{\nthderiv[4]{f}(0)}{3!} \, t^3 + \frac{\nthderiv[5]{f}(0)}{4!} \, t^4 + \dotsb </mrow>
	<mrow> = \;\; \amp f'(0) + \frac{f''(0)}{2} \cdot (2 t) + \frac{f'''(0)}{3!} \cdot (3 t^2) + \frac{\nthderiv[4]{f}(0)}{4!} \cdot (4 t^3) + \frac{\nthderiv[5]{f}(0)}{5!} \cdot \bbrac{5 t^4} + \dotsb </mrow>
</md>.
Again, let's line this Taylor series up with the one for f.
<md>
	\begin{array}{cccccccccc}
		f\colon \amp f(0) \amp + \amp f'(0) \, t \amp + \amp {\displaystyle \frac{f''(0)}{2} \, t^2} \amp + \amp {\displaystyle \frac{f'''(0)}{3!} \, t^3} \amp + \amp \dotsb
		\\
		g\colon \amp \amp \amp f'(0) \amp + \amp {\displaystyle \frac{f''(0)}{2} \cdot (2 t)} \amp + \amp {\displaystyle \frac{f'''(0)}{3!} \cdot (3 t^2)} \amp + \amp \dotsb
	\end{array}
</md>
This time it appears that each term of the series for <m>g = f'</m> can be obtained by <term>term-by-term differentiation</term> of the series for <m>f</m>
(see <xref ref="pattern-deriv-power" />).
</p>

<p>
It's important to note at this point that the Taylor series for <m>F</m> and <m>f'</m> above don't necessarily converge to those respective functions for all <m>t</m>.
We'll address questions of convergence in <xref ref="subsection-power-series-convergence-int-diff-pow-series" />,
but for now the next two examples give us hope that term-by-term operations yield the desired results.
</p>

<example xml:id="example-power-series-int-diff-exp">
	<title>Integrating/differentiating the exponential Taylor series</title>

	<p>
	From <xref ref="example-power-series-natural-exp-taylor-remainder" /> we know that for all <m>t</m> we have
	<md><mrow xml:id="equation-power-series-exp-taylor" tag="star"> e^t = 1 + t + \frac{t^2}{2} + \frac{t^3}{3!} + \frac{t^4}{4!} + \dotsb </mrow></md>.
	</p>

	<p>
	Applying term-by-term integration to this series we obtain
	<md> t + \frac{t^2}{2} + \frac{t^3 / 3}{2} + \frac{t^4 / 4}{3!} + \frac{t^5 / 5}{4!} + \dotsb </md>.
	However, consolidating denominators in each term,
	we see that this series is identical to <xref ref="equation-power-series-exp-taylor" />,
	except that it is missing the constant term.
	So term-by-term integration has resulted in a power series that converges to <m>e^t - 1</m>,
	which conveniently agrees with <xref ref="pattern-exp-integral" />.
	</p>

	<p>
	Applying term-by-term differentiation to <xref ref="equation-power-series-exp-taylor" /> yields
	<md> 0 + 1 + \frac{2 t}{2} + \frac{3 t^2}{3!} + \frac{4 t^3}{4!} + \dotsb </md>,
	which simplifies to the Taylor series for the exponential function,
	agreeing with <xref ref="pattern-deriv-exp" />.
	</p>

</example>

<example xml:id="example-power-series-int-diff-cos">
	<title>Integrating/differentiating the Taylor series for cosine</title>

	<p>
	From <xref ref="exercise-power-series-cosine-taylor-remainder" /> we know that for all <m>t</m> we have
	<md> \cos(t) = \sum_{m = 0}^{\infty} \frac{{(-1)}^m}{(2m)!} \; t^{2 m} </md>.
	</p>

	<p>
	Let's integrate each term of this series:
	<md>
		<mrow>
			\sum_{m = 0}^{\infty} \left( \ccmiint{\frac{{(-1)}^m}{(2m)!} \; t^{2 m}}{t} \right)
			\amp = \sum_{m = 0}^{\infty} \left( \frac{{(-1)}^m}{(2m)!} \; \ccmiint{t^{2 m}}{t} \right)
		</mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \sum_{m = 0}^{\infty} \frac{{(-1)}^m}{(2m)!} \; \frac{t^{2 m + 1}}{2 m + 1} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \sum_{m = 0}^{\infty} \frac{{(-1)}^m}{(2m)! \cdot (2 m + 1)} \; t^{2 m + 1} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \sum_{m = 0}^{\infty} \frac{{(-1)}^m}{(2 m + 1)!} \; t^{2 m + 1} </mrow>
	</md>.
	If you completed <xref ref="exercise-power-series-taylor-for-sine" />,
	you will recognized this result as precisely the Taylor series at <m>t = 0</m> for the sine function,
	conveniently agreeing with <xref ref="pattern-periodic-int-cos" />.
	</p>

	<p>
	Now let's differentiate each term of the Taylor series for cosine.
	Since the first term in the series is a constant whose derivative is <m>0</m>,
	we will simply shift indices in the term-by-term differentiated series.
	<md>
		<mrow>
			\sum_{m = 0}^{\infty} \opddt \left( \frac{{(-1)}^m}{(2m)!} \; t^{2 m} \right)
			\amp = \sum_{m = 0}^{\infty} \frac{{(-1)}^m}{(2m)!} \; \ddt{(t^{2 m})}
		</mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \sum_{m = 1}^{\infty} \frac{{(-1)}^m}{(2m)!} \cdot (2 m t^{2 m - 1}) </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \sum_{m = 1}^{\infty} \frac{{(-1)}^m (2 m)}{(2m)!} \; t^{2 m - 1} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \sum_{m = 1}^{\infty} \frac{{(-1)}^m}{(2 m - 1)!} \; t^{2 m - 1} </mrow>
	</md>
	Let's shift the index so that our sum begins at index <m>0</m> by substituting <m>j = m - 1</m>.
	Under this substitution,
	<md><mrow> m \amp = j + 1 \text{,} \amp 2 m - 1 \amp = 2 j + 1 \text{,} </mrow></md>
	and our differentiated sum becomes
	<md>
		<mrow>
			\sum_{m = 1}^{\infty} \frac{{(-1)}^m}{(2 m - 1)!} \; t^{2 m - 1}
			\amp = \sum_{j = 0}^{\infty} \frac{{(-1)}^{j + 1}}{(2 j + 1)!} \; t^{2 j + 1}
		</mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \sum_{j = 0}^{\infty} \frac{(-1) \cdot {(-1)}^j}{(2 j + 1)!} \; t^{2 j + 1} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = - \sum_{j = 0}^{\infty} \frac{{(-1)}^j}{(2 j + 1)!} \; t^{2 j + 1} </mrow>
	</md>.
	Again, this new series is the Taylor series at <m>t = 0</m> for the sine function,
	except for the extra negative sign out front,
	and so this result agrees with <xref ref="pattern-deriv-cos" />.
	</p>

</example>

</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="subsection-power-series-convergence-int-diff-pow-series">
<title>Convergence of integrated/differentiated power series</title>

<p>
Naturally, questions of convergence arise.
<ul>
	<li>
		For <m>F</m> an antiderivative of <m>f</m>,
		do the Taylor series for <m>f</m>, <m>F</m>, and <m>f'</m> all have the same interval of convergence?
	</li>
	<li> For what values of <m>t</m> does each series converge to the value of the function from which it was created? </li>
</ul>
We'll address the question of convergence more generally.
</p>

<fact xml:id="fact-power-series-diff-int-termwise-converge">
	<title>Convergence of differentiated/integrated power series</title>

	<statement><p>
		If the power series <m>\sum a_k t^k</m> has positive (possibly infinite) radius of convergence <m>R</m>,
		then the power series
		<md><mrow>
			\amp \sum_{k = 0}^\infty \frac{a_k}{k + 1} \, t^{k + 1} \text{,} \amp
			\amp \sum_{k = 1}^\infty k a_k t^{k - 1} \text{,}
		</mrow></md>
		obtained from <m>\sum a_k t^k</m> by term-by-term integration and differentiation,
		respectively,
		also have radius of convergence <m>R</m>.
	</p></statement>

	<proof><title>Justification for the differentiated series</title>

		<p>
		First suppose <m>c</m> lies in <m>0 \lt t \lt R</m>.
		(A similar argument as to the one provided below can be made for negative <m>c</m>.)
		We know from <xref ref="fact-power-series-radius" /> that <m>\sum a_k c^k</m> converges absolutely,
		and in fact so does <m>\sum a_k d^k</m> for any value of <m>d</m> between <m>c</m> and <m>R</m>.
		Choose such a value of <m>d</m>
		(for example, <m>d</m> could be the average of <m>c</m> and <m>R</m>).
		We will compare the absolute convergence of the differentiated series <m>\sum k a_k c^{k - 1}</m> with <m>\sum a_k d^k</m>.
		</p>

		<p>
		One may easily verify with the Ratio Test that the series <m>\sum k t^{k - 1}</m> has radius of convergence <m>1</m>.
		Since <m>c / d \lt 1</m>,
		the series <m>\sum k {(c/d)}^{k - 1}</m> converges absolutely,
		and the sequence of terms <m>\bbseq{n {(c/d)}^{n - 1}}</m> must converge to <m>0</m>.
		Therefore, any constant multiple of this sequence must converge to <m>0</m>.
		In particular, if we divide each term by <m>d</m>,
		we have
		<md> \lrseq{ \frac{n c^{n - 1}}{d^n} } \to 0 </md>.
		As such,
		there must exist some tail of this sequence
		(starting at index <m>N</m>, say)
		completely contained in the open range <m>(-1, 1)</m>.
		As both <m>c</m> and <m>d</m> are positive,
		for all <m>n \ge N</m> we have
		<md alignment="gather">
			<mrow> \frac{n c^{n - 1}}{d^n} \lt 1 </mrow>
			<mrow> n c^{n - 1} \lt d^n </mrow>
		</md>.
		We may multiply this inequality by the non-negative value <m>\abs{a_n}</m>,
		and take absolute value of everything since these are all positive values,
		to obtain <md> \abs{n a_n c^{n - 1}} \lt \abs{a_n d^n} </md>.
		This is the comparison we were seeking:
		since <m>\sum a_k d^k</m> converges absolutely,
		so must <m>\sum n a_n c^{n - 1}</m>.
		</p>

		<p>
		Now suppose <m>c</m> is outside of <m>-R \le t \le R</m>.
		Again we will assume that <m>c</m> is positive,
		as a similar argument will work in the case that <m>c</m> is negative.
		We essentially make a <q>reflected</q> argument of the one above,
		reflected at <m>R</m>.
		Again choose <m>d</m> between <m>R</m> and <m>c</m>,
		which will also lie outside of the radius of convergence of <m>\sum a_k t^k</m>.
		Then <m>c/d \gt 1</m> and so
		<md> \lrseq{ n {\left(\frac{c}{d}\right)}^{n - 1} } \to \infty </md>.
		Any constant multiple of this sequence will also diverge to infinity.
		In particular,
		dividing every term by <m>d</m> gives us
		<md> \lrseq{ n \frac{c^{n - 1}}{d^n} } \to \infty </md>,
		and so there is some tail of this sequence where the terms become and stay greater than <m>1</m>.
		Performing similar manipulations as in the convergent case above,
		we may say that there is an <m>N</m> where <md> \abs{n a_n c^{n - 1}} \gt \abs{a_n d^n} </md> for all <m>n \ge N</m>,
		hence we conclude that <m>\sum n a_n c^{n - 1}</m> diverges absolutely by comparison with <m>\sum a_k d^k</m>.
		</p>

	</proof>

	<proof><title>Justification for the integrated series</title>

		<p>
		First suppose <m>c</m> lies in <m>-R \lt t \lt R</m>.
		We know from <xref ref="fact-power-series-radius" /> that <m>\sum a_k c^k</m> converges absolutely,
		and clearly <md> \abs{\frac{a_n c^n}{n + 1}} \lt \abs{a_n c^n} </md>
		for all <m>n</m>,
		so that <m>\sum \abs{a_k c^k / (k + 1)}</m> converges by comparison.
		But then so does <md> \abs{c} \cdot \sum_{k = 0}^\infty \abs{\frac{a_k}{k + 1} \, c^k} = \sum_{k = 0}^\infty \abs{\frac{a_k}{k + 1} \, c^{k + 1}}</md>.
		Therefore, <m>\sum a_k c^{k + 1} / (k + 1)</m> converges absolutely.
		</p>

		<p>
		Now consider a value of <m>c</m> outside of <m>-R \le t \le R</m>.
		If <m>\sum a_k c^{k + 1} / (k + 1)</m> converged,
		then <m>c</m> would be within the interval of convergence of the series <m>\sum a_k x^{k + 1} / (k + 1)</m>.
		If we differentiate this series term-by-term,
		the resulting series would have the same radius of convergence.
		But differentiating that series term-by-term yields
		<md> \sum_{k = 1}^\infty a_k \cdot \frac{(k + 1) x^k}{k + 1} = \sum_{k = 1}^\infty a_k x^k </md>,
		which is simply a tail of the original series <m>\sum a_k x^k</m>,
		and hence has the same radius of convergence <m>R</m>.
		Since we assumed <m>c</m> to be outside of this radius of convergence,
		we have a contradiction,
		and we conclude that <m>\sum a_k c^{k + 1} / (k + 1)</m> must diverge.
		</p>

	</proof>

</fact>

<p>
So integrated/differentiated power series converge on the same interval that the original power series does.
But to what do they converge?
Thankfully, the results of
<xref ref="example-power-series-int-diff-exp" />
and
<xref ref="example-power-series-int-diff-cos" />
are not coincidences or special cases.
But justifying this is beyond the scope of this text.
<!-- TODO if uniform convergence is ever added can reconsider -->
</p>

<theorem xml:id="theorem-power-series-deriv-antideriv-pow-series">
	<title>Derivatives/antiderivatives of power series</title>

	<p>
	Suppose the power series <m>\sum a_k t^k</m> has positive (possibly infinite) radius of convergence <m>R</m>,
	and let <m>f(t)</m> be the function defined by this power series on its (open) interval of convergence <m>-R \lt t \lt R</m>.
	<ol>

		<li xml:id="theorem-power-series-deriv-antideriv-pow-series-anti">
			The function <m>f</m> is continuous on <m>-R \lt t \lt R</m>,
			and the term-by-term-integrated series
			<md> F(t) = \sum_{k = 0}^\infty \left( \ccmiint{a_k t^k}{t} \right) = \sum_{k = 0}^\infty \frac{a_k}{k + 1} \; t^{k + 1} </md>
			is an antiderivative for <m>f</m> on that domain.
		</li>

		<li xml:id="theorem-power-series-deriv-antideriv-pow-series-deriv">
			The function <m>f</m> is differentiable on <m>-R \lt t \lt R</m>,
			and its derivative is equal to the function determined by the term-by-term-differentiated power series
			<md> f'(t) = \sum_{k = 0}^\infty \opddt (a_k t^k) = \sum_{k = 1}^\infty k a_k t^{k - 1} </md>.
		</li>

	</ol>

	</p>

</theorem>

<p>
While the justification for <xref ref="theorem-power-series-deriv-antideriv-pow-series-deriv" text="type-local">Statement</xref>
of <xref ref="theorem-power-series-deriv-antideriv-pow-series" /> is beyond the scope of this text,
<!-- TODO if uniform convergence is added then reword -->
it can be used to justify <xref ref="theorem-power-series-deriv-antideriv-pow-series-anti" text="type-local">Statement</xref>.
Every differentiable function is continuous
(<xref ref="pattern-avg-rate-diff-implies-cont" />),
and we can use term-by-term differentiation of the power series expression for <m>F(t)</m> to arrive back at <m>f</m>,
demonstrating that <m>F'(t) = f(t)</m>.
</p>

<p> We can also extend <xref ref="theorem-power-series-deriv-antideriv-pow-series" /> to higher derivatives. </p>

<corollary xml:id="corollary-power-series-higher-deriv">
	<p>
	If <m>f(t) = \sum a_k t^k</m> on <m>-R \lt t \lt R</m>,
	then <md> \nthderiv{f}(t) = \sum_{k = 0}^\infty \opnthddt (a_k t^k) = \sum_{k = n}^\infty \frac{k!}{(k - n)!} \; a_k t^{k - n} </md>.
	</p>
</corollary>

</subsection>

<subsection>
<title>Using differentiation/integration to compute power series</title>

<p>
Instead of computing higher and higher derivatives of a function in order to compute its Taylor series,
an alternative is to use term-by-term integration of a known power series representation for a function to obtain a power series representation for its antiderivative or its derivatives.
</p>

<example xml:id="example-power-series-deriv-geom">
	<title>Derivative of the geometric series</title>
	<p>
	We know that the geometric series <m>\sum r^k</m> converges to <m>1 / (1 - r)</m> for <m>-1 \lt r \lt 1</m>
	(<xref ref="pattern-series-geometric" />).
	Trading <m>r</m> for our preferred variable <m>t</m>,
	we get a power series representation of the function <m>f(t) = 1 / (1 - t)</m> with radius of convergence <m>R = 1</m>:
	<md> \frac{1}{1 - t} = 1 + t + t^2 + t^3 + \dotsb </md>.
	Now <md> \opddt\left( \frac{1}{1 - t} \right) = \frac{1}{{(1 - t)}^2} </md>,
	so we may differentiate the series for <m>f</m> term-by-term to obtain
	<md> \frac{1}{{(1 - t)}^2} = 1 + 2 t + 3 t^2 + 4 t^3 + \dotsb </md>,
	valid on domain <m>-1 \lt t \lt 1</m>.
	</p>
</example>

<exercise><p>
	Use <xref ref="corollary-power-series-higher-deriv" /> to continue the pattern of <xref ref="example-power-series-deriv-geom" />,
	obtaining a general power series representation for every power <m>1 / {(1 - t)}^{m + 1}</m>, <m>m \ge 0</m>.
</p></exercise>

<example>
	<title>Integral of the geometric series</title>
	<p>
	We know that <md> \sum_{k = 0}^\infty t^k = \frac{1}{1 - t} \text{,} \qquad -1 \lt t \lt 1 \text{.} </md>
	Integrating both sides,
	we obtain <md> \sum_{k = 0}^\infty \frac{t^{k + 1}}{k + 1} = - \ln(1 - t) + C </md>.
	(On domain <m>-1 \lt t \lt 1</m> there is no need to include absolute value brackets inside the logarithm.)
	Both the infinite series and the logarithm evaluate to <m>0</m> at <m>t = 0</m>,
	so we conclude that <m>C = 0</m>.
	Shifting indices in the series using the substitution <m>m = k + 1</m>,
	we arrive at <md> \sum_{m = 1}^\infty \frac{t^m}{m} = - \ln(1 - t) </md>.
	In particular,
	for <m>t = 1/2</m> we have
	<md> \sum_{m = 1}^\infty \frac{{(1/2)}^m}{m} = - \ln\left(\frac{1}{2}\right) = \ln(2) </md>.
	This provides us with an interesting representation of <m>\ln(2)</m> as an infinite series:
	<md> \ln(2) = \sum_{m = 1}^\infty \frac{1}{m 2^m} </md>.
	</p>
</example>

<example>
	<title>Integral of the natural logarithm</title>

	<p>
	First, we know that <m>\ln'(t) = 1 / t</m>,
	and <md> \frac{1}{t} = \frac{1}{1 - r} \quad\text{for}\quad r = 1 - t </md>.
	So we can again use the <xref ref="pattern-series-geometric" text="title" /> to obtain a power series representation:
	<md>
		\frac{1}{t} = \frac{1}{1 - r}
		= \sum_{k = 0}^\infty r^k
		= \sum_{k = 0}^\infty {(1 - t)}^k
		= \sum_{k = 0}^\infty {(-1)}^k {(t - 1)}^k
	</md>.
	Note that this power series expression converges for <m>-1 \lt r \lt 1</m>,
	which translates into <m>0 \lt t \lt 2</m>.
	</p>

	<p>
	Now integrate both sides of <md> \frac{1}{t} = \sum_{k = 0}^\infty {(-1)}^k {(t - 1)}^k </md>
	to arrive at
	<md> \ln(t) + C = \sum_{k = 0}^\infty \frac{{(-1)}^k}{k + 1} {(t - 1)}^{k + 1} </md>.
	Both <m>\ln(t)</m> and the infinite series evaluation to <m>0</m> at <m>t = 1</m>,
	so we conclude that <m>C = 0</m>.
	Shifting indices in the series using the substitution <m>m = k + 1</m>,
	we arrive at
	<md><mrow xml:id="equation-power-series-ln-taylor" tag="dagger">
		\ln(t) = \sum_{m = 1}^\infty \frac{{(-1)}^{m - 1}}{m} {(t - 1)}^m
	</mrow></md>.
	</p>

	<aside><title>Power versus Taylor/Maclaurin series</title><p>
		Compare the power series representation for <m>\ln(t)</m> obtained here with the Maclaurin series for <m>\ln(1 + t)</m> obtained in
		<xref ref="example-power-series-shifted-logarithm" />.
	</p></aside>

	<p>
	Finally, we will integrate term-by-term once again to obtain an antiderivative of <m>\ln(t)</m>:
	<md>
		<mrow>
			\ccmiint{\ln(t)}{t}
			\amp = \sum_{m = 1}^\infty \left( \ccmiint{\frac{{(-1)}^{m - 1}}{m} {(t - 1)}^m}{t} \right)
		</mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \sum_{m = 1}^\infty \left( \frac{{(-1)}^{m - 1}}{m} \ccmiint{{(t - 1)}^m}{t} \right) </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \sum_{m = 1}^\infty \frac{{(-1)}^{m - 1}}{m} \frac{{(t - 1)}^{m + 1}}{m + 1} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \sum_{m = 1}^\infty \frac{{(-1)}^{m - 1}}{m (m + 1)} \; {(t - 1)}^{m + 1} </mrow>
	</md>.
	Using <md> \frac{1}{m (m + 1)} = \frac{1}{m} - \frac{1}{m + 1} </md> we can rearrange:
	<md>
		<mrow>
			\ccmiint{\ln(t)}{t}
			\amp = \sum_{m = 1}^\infty \left( \frac{{(-1)}^{m - 1}}{m} - \frac{{(-1)}^{m - 1}}{(m + 1)} \right) \; {(t - 1)}^{m + 1}
		</mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \sum_{m = 1}^\infty \left( \frac{{(-1)}^{m - 1}}{m} + \frac{{(-1)}^m}{(m + 1)} \right) \; {(t - 1)}^{m + 1} </mrow>
	</md>.
	We can then split this into two series:
	<md><mrow xml:id="equation-power-series-int-ln-taylor" tag="ddagger">
		\ccmiint{\ln(t)}{t}
		= \sum_{m = 1}^\infty \frac{{(-1)}^{m - 1}}{m} \; {(t - 1)}^{m + 1}
		+ \sum_{m = 1}^\infty \frac{{(-1)}^m}{(m + 1)} \; {(t - 1)}^{m + 1}
	</mrow></md>.
	Now, the <em>first</em> series in
	<xref ref="equation-power-series-int-ln-taylor" />,
	resembles the <em>second</em> power series representation for <m>\ln(t)</m> in
	<xref ref="equation-power-series-ln-taylor" />:
	<md>
		\sum_{m = 1}^\infty \frac{{(-1)}^{m - 1}}{m} \; {(t - 1)}^{m + 1}
		= (t - 1) \sum_{m = 1}^\infty \frac{{(-1)}^{m - 1}}{m} \; {(t - 1)}^m
		= (t - 1) \ln(t)
	</md>.
	And the <em>second</em> series in
	<xref ref="equation-power-series-int-ln-taylor" />,
	resembles the <em>first</em> power series representation for <m>\ln(t)</m> in
	<xref ref="equation-power-series-ln-taylor" />:
	<md>
		<mrow>
			\sum_{m = 1}^\infty \frac{{(-1)}^m}{(m + 1)} \; {(t - 1)}^{m + 1}
			\amp = \sum_{k = 1}^\infty \frac{{(-1)}^k}{(k + 1)} \; {(t - 1)}^{k + 1}
		</mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = -(t - 1) + (t - 1) + \sum_{k = 1}^\infty \frac{{(-1)}^k}{(k + 1)} \; {(t - 1)}^{k + 1} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = -(t - 1) + \frac{{(-1)}^0}{(0 + 1)} \; {(t - 1)}^{0 + 1} + \sum_{k = 1}^\infty \frac{{(-1)}^k}{(k + 1)} \; {(t - 1)}^{k + 1} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = -(t - 1) + \sum_{k = 0}^\infty \frac{{(-1)}^k}{(k + 1)} \; {(t - 1)}^{k + 1} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = 1 - t + \ln(t) </mrow>
	</md>.
	Adding these back together yields
	<md>
		\ccmiint{\ln(t)}{t}
		= (t - 1) \ln(t) + 1 - t + \ln(t)
		= t \ln(t) - t + 1
	</md>.
	For an indefinite integral we should really have an <em>arbitrary</em> constant of integration,
	so we conclude that
	<md> \ccmiint{\ln(t)}{t} = t \ln(t) - t + C </md>.
	</p>

	<aside><title>Previous knowledge</title><p>
		If you have previously learned the method of integration called <term>integration by parts</term>,
		then you likely already know that our result here for the integral of <m>\ln(t)</m> matches what can be obtained by that method more simply.
	</p></aside>

</example>

<p> We can also use term-by-term integration to help estimate definite integral values. </p>

<example>
	<title> Estimating a definite integral with partial sums </title>

	<p>
	Suppose we want to estimate the definite integral below to within <m>\pm {10}^{-10}</m>.
	<md> \ccmint{0}{1/2}{\frac{1}{1 + t^7}}{t} </md>
	Recall that we can use <em>any</em> choice of antiderivative for the integrand function to compute a definite integral
	(<xref ref="pattern-fund-thm-def-int-by-antideriv" />).
	In particular,
	we can create an antiderivative through term-by-term integration of a power series representation of the integrand function.
	Conveniently, our integrand can be interpreted as the sum of a geometric series with <m>r = -t^7</m>:
	<md alignment="gather">
		<mrow> f(t) = \frac{1}{1 + t^7} = \frac{1}{1 - (-t^7)} = \sum_{k = 0}^\infty {(-t^7)}^k = \sum_{k = 0}^\infty {(-1)}^k t^{7 k} </mrow>
		<mrow> F(t) = \ccmiint{f(t)}{t} = \sum_{k = 0}^\infty {(-1)}^k \frac{t^{7 k + 1}}{7 k + 1} </mrow>
	</md>
	Our power series representation of <m>f</m> is valid for <m>-1 \lt r \lt 1</m>,
	which for <m>r = -t^7</m> is equivalent to the domain <m>-1 \lt t \lt 1</m> and contains our domain of integration.
	And by <xref ref="theorem-power-series-deriv-antideriv-pow-series" />,
	our antiderivative power series is also valid on that domain.
	</p>

	<p>
	We have <md> \ccmint{0}{1/2}{\frac{1}{1 + t^7}}{t} = F(1/2) - F(0) </md>,
	but every term in our power series for <m>F</m> involves a non-trivial power of <m>t</m>.
	So there is no constant term and <m>F(0) = 0</m>,
	which means that we only need to estimate <md> F(1/2) = \sum_{k = 0}^\infty \frac{{(-1)}^k}{(7 k + 1) 2^{7 k + 1}} </md>.
	This is an alternating series with terms whose absolute value are decreasing,
	so we may apply <xref ref="fact-series-estimate-alternating-sum" /> to estimate
	<md> F(1/2) \approx \left( \sum_{k = 0}^n \frac{{(-1)}^k}{(7 k + 1) 2^{7 k + 1}} \right) \pm \frac{1}{(7 n + 8) 2^{7 n + 8}} </md>,
	where the error bound is the magnitude of the <m>\nth[(n + 1)]</m> term in the sum.
	What is the smallest value of <m>n</m> so that this error bound is less than <m>{10}^{-10}</m>?
	Then denominator is first larger than <m>{10}^{10}</m> for <m>n = 3</m>,
	so we only need the first four terms of the sum (indices <m>k = 0</m> to <m>k = 3</m>, inclusive):
	<md>
		\ccmint{0}{1/2}{\frac{1}{1 + t^7}}{t}
		= F(1/2)
		\approx
		\frac{1}{2}
		- \frac{1}{8 \cdot 2^8}
		+ \frac{1}{15 \cdot 2^{15}}
		- \frac{1}{22 \cdot 2^{22}}
	</md>.
	</p>

</example>

</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="subsection-power-series-abel">
<title>Convergence at endpoints: Abel's Theorem</title>

<example xml:id="example-power-series-endpoints-of-shifted-logarithm">
	<title>Endpoint convergence of a shifted logarithm</title>

	<p>
	Suppose we would like to have a power series representation of the shifted logarithm function <m>f(t) = \ln(1 + t)</m>.
	We have <m>f'(t) = 1/(1 + t)</m>,
	and we may interpret this as the sum of a geometric series with <m>r = -t</m>:
	<md> f'(t) = \frac{1}{1 - (-t)} = \sum_{k = 0}^\infty {(-t)}^k = 1 - t + t^2 - t^3 + \dotsb </md>.
	This power series representation is valid for <m>-1 \lt r \lt 1</m>,
	which for <m>r = -t</m> is equivalent to the domain <m>-1 \lt t \lt 1</m>.
	Integrating this power series term-by-term will result in an antiderivative of <m>f'(t)</m>,
	which must then be a vertical shift of <m>f(t)</m>:
	<md>
		f(t) + C
		= \sum_{k = 0}^\infty \left( \ccmiint{{(-1)}^k t^k}{t} \right)
		= \sum_{k = 0}^\infty \frac{{(-1)}^k t^{k + 1}}{k + 1}
		= \sum_{m = 1}^\infty \frac{{(-1)}^{m - 1} t^m}{m}
	</md>,
	for some constant <m>C</m>.
	We have <m>f(0) = 0</m>,
	and the power series has no constant term,
	so we must have <m>C = 0</m> and
	<md> \ln(1 + t) = \sum_{m = 1}^\infty \frac{{(-1)}^{m - 1}}{m} \; t^m </md>.
	(Compare with the Taylor series for this function that we computed in <xref ref="example-power-series-shifted-logarithm" />.)
	</p>

	<p>
	Since our series for <m>f'(t)</m> converges on <m>-1 \lt t \lt 1</m>,
	<xref ref="theorem-power-series-deriv-antideriv-pow-series" /> implies that our series for <m>\ln(1 + t)</m> converges on that same domain,
	and for each value of <m>t</m> in that domain the series converges to the value of <m>\ln(t)</m>.
	For <m>t = -1</m> the series is a harmonic series,
	and hence diverges,
	which is to be expected since <m>f(-1)</m> is undefined.
	For <m>t = 1</m> the series is an <em>alternating</em> harmonic series,
	which we know converges.
	But what does it converge to?
	We hope that it converges to <m>f(1) = ln(2)</m>.
	</p>

</example>

<theorem xml:id="theorem-power-series-abel">
	<title>Abel's Theorem</title>
	<p>
	Suppose <m>f</m> is a function defined on domain <m>-R \le t \le R</m>,
	and <m>\sum a_k t^k</m> is a power series with radius of convergence <m>R</m> that converges to the value of <m>f(t)</m> for each <m>t</m> in the domain <m>-R \lt t \lt R</m>.
	<ul>

		<li>
			If <m>f</m> is continuous from the left at <m>t = R</m> and <m>\sum a_k R^k</m> converges,
			then it converges to <m>f(R)</m>.
		</li>

		<li>
			If <m>f</m> is continuous from the right at <m>t = -R</m> and <m>\sum a_k (-R)^k</m> converges,
			then it converges to <m>f(-R)</m>.
		</li>

	</ul>
	</p>
</theorem>

<example>
	<title>Abel's Theorem for a shifted logarithm</title>
	<p>
	Returning to <xref ref="example-power-series-endpoints-of-shifted-logarithm" />,
	the function <m>f(t) = \ln(1 + t)</m> is continuous on its entire domain <m>t \gt -1</m>,
	so we may say that it is continuous from the left at <m>t = 1</m>.
	Abel's Theorem lets us conclude that the alternating harmonic series <m>\sum {(-1)}^{k - 1} / k</m> converges to <m>\ln(2)</m>,
	as claimed in <xref ref="example-series-reordering-terms-different-results" />.
	</p>
</example>

</subsection>

</section>

<section>
<title>Power series versus Taylor series</title>

<p>
In the examples in this chapter we have often used known sum of the <xref ref="pattern-series-geometric" text="title" /> to quickly obtain a power series representation of a function.
How does such a power series compare to the Taylor series based at <m>t = 0</m>?
Is it possible to have two different power series representations for a given function,
both <q>based</q> at the same point?
</p>

<example xml:id="example-power-series-taylor-of-geometric">
	<title>Compare the geometric series with the Taylor series of its sum</title>
	<p>
	We know <md> \frac{1}{1 - t} = \sum_{k = 0}^\infty t^k \text{,} \qquad -1 \lt t \lt 1 \text{.} </md>
	Write <m>f(t) = 1 / (1 - t)</m>.
	Try computing the first four derivatives of <m>f</m>;
	you should observe the pattern <md> \nthderiv{f}(t) = \frac{n!}{{(1 - t)}^{n + 1}} </md>,
	from which we obtain <m>\nthderiv{f}(0) = n!</m>.
	Using this in the Taylor series formula,
	we have
	<md>
		<mrow> \frac{1}{1 - t} \amp = \sum_{k = 0}^\infty \frac{\nthderiv[k]{f}(0)}{k!} \; t^k </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \sum_{k = 0}^\infty \frac{k!}{k!} \; t^k </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \sum_{k = 0}^\infty t^k </mrow>
	</md>,
	which is simply the geometric series again.
	</p>
</example>

<exercise>
	<title>Taylor series of the reflected geometric series</title>
	<p>
	Perform the same analysis as in <xref ref="example-power-series-taylor-of-geometric" /> for the function <md> f(t) = \frac{1}{1 + t} = \frac{1}{1 - (-t)} </md>.
	On the one hand,
	obtain a power series representation for <m>f</m> by interpreting its formula as the sum of a geometric series,
	and on the other hand compute the Taylor series for <m>f</m> based at <m>t = 0</m>.
	Compare.
	</p>
</exercise>

<fact>
	<title>Taylor series for a power series function</title>

	<statement><p>
		Suppose <m>\sum a_k t^k</m> has positive (possibly infinite) radius of convergence <m>R</m>.
		If <m>f</m> represents the function defined by the power series,
		<md> f(t) = \sum_{k = 0}^\infty a_k t^k \text{,} \qquad -R \lt t \lt R </md>,
		then the Taylor series for <m>f</m> based at <m>t = 0</m> is <m>\sum a_k t^k</m>.
	</p></statement>

	<proof>
		<title>Idea of justification</title>
		<p> To compute the Taylor series, apply the differentiation formula for power series in <xref ref="corollary-power-series-higher-deriv" />. </p>
	</proof>

</fact>

<corollary>
	<title>Taylor series for a derivative/antiderivative function</title>
	<p><ol>

		<li>
			For a continuous function <m>f</m>,
			one may obtain the Taylor series for an antiderivative <m>F(t)</m> by term-by-term integration of the Taylor series for <m>f</m>
			(with the possible addition of a vertical shift).
		</li>

		<li>
			For differentiable function <m>f</m>,
			one may obtain the Taylor series for <m>f'(t)</m> by term-by-term differentiation of the Taylor series for <m>f</m>.
		</li>

	</ol></p>
</corollary>

<example>
	<title>Determining the Taylor series for an antiderivative of a continuous function</title>
	<p>
	From the <xref ref="theorem-fund-thm" text="title" />,
	we may conclude that every continuous function has an antiderivative.
	(See <xref ref="fact-fund-thm-continuous-has-antideriv" />.)
	For example,
	the continuous function <m>f(t) = e^{t^2}</m> must have an antiderivative,
	but you are unlikely to guess a formula for it without using an integral sign.
	However, if we are willing to use an integral sign,
	we can construct an antiderivative of <m>f</m>:
	<md> F(t) = \ccmint{0}{t}{e^{u^2}}{u} </md>.
	What is the Taylor series for <m>F</m>?
	We know that the Taylor series for the natural exponential function is <m>\exp(t) = \sum t^k / k!</m>,
	with infinite radius of convergence.
	(See <xref ref="example-power-series-exp-taylor" />.)
	Substituting <m>t^2</m> into this series yields <m>e^{t^2} = \sum t^{2 k} / k!</m>,
	and by integrating we obtain <md> \ccmiint{e^{t^2}}{t} = C + \sum_{k = 0}^\infty \frac{t^{2 k + 1}}{k! (2 k + 1)} </md>,
	where <m>C</m> is an arbitrary constant of integration.
	The specific antiderivative <m>F(t)</m> must be one of the infinite family of antiderivatives above,
	and from <m>F(0) = 0</m> we conclude that it is the antiderivative where <m>C = 0</m>:
	<md> \ccmint{0}{t}{e^{u^2}}{u} = \sum_{k = 0}^\infty \frac{t^{2 k + 1}}{k! (2 k + 1)} </md>.
	As we know that integrating a power series does not affect the radius of convergence,
	this power series representation of <m>F</m> is valid for all <m>t</m>.
	</p>
</example>

</section>


